<paper id="1482974618"><title>Logical Characterizations of Nonmonotonic TMSs</title><year>1989</year><authors><author org="Cornell University;" id="705676171">Charles Elkan</author></authors><n_citation>9</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>152625262</reference><reference>192230374</reference><reference>1538136274</reference><reference>1647734625</reference><reference>1672891595</reference><reference>1966552757</reference><reference>1976303542</reference><reference>2073670920</reference><reference>2111009794</reference></references><venue id="1163686456" type="C">Mathematical Foundations of Computer Science</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-51486-4_69</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.0">Logic program</keyword><keyword weight="0.4224">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.40671">Combinatorics</keyword><keyword weight="0.68199">Autoepistemic logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.43928">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.42881">Independent set</keyword><keyword weight="0.65062">Non-monotonic logic</keyword><keyword weight="0.60633">Logic programming</keyword><keyword weight="0.4884">Rotation formalisms in three dimensions</keyword><keyword weight="0.48234">Semantics</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Truth maintenance</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Nonmonotonic truth maintenance systems (TMSs) have been widely used without a clear appreciation of their capabilities and limitations. This paper characterizes the logical inferences performed by a nonmonotonic TMS in terms of two formalisms of independent interest, namely logic programming with the stable set semantics and autoepistemic logic. The paper also shows that implementing a nonmonotonic TMS is an NP-complete problem.</abstract></paper>